================================================================================
VALQUIRIA SPACE ANALOG RESEARCH PROJECT - ADDITIONAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
================================================================================

This software is part of the Valquiria Space Analog Physiological Data Analysis 
Suite, developed for scientific research in aerospace medicine and space analog 
simulation studies.

RESEARCH AND EDUCATIONAL PURPOSE:
This software is primarily intended for academic research, educational training, 
and scientific collaboration in the fields of:
- Aerospace medicine and physiology
- Space analog simulation research  
- Heart rate variability (HRV) analysis
- Autonomic nervous system assessment
- Physiological adaptation studies

IMPORTANT DISCLAIMERS AND PROHIBITED USES:
⚠️  This software is NOT approved for and shall NOT be used for:
    • Military operational deployment or mission-critical systems
    • Clinical diagnosis, treatment, or patient care
    • Operational crew health monitoring in real missions
    • Safety-critical applications where human life depends on the software
    • Commercial health monitoring services without proper validation

ATTRIBUTION AND CITATION REQUIREMENTS:
If you use this software in research or publications, you MUST:
1. Cite the software using proper academic citation format (see README.md)
2. Acknowledge the Valquiria Space Analog Simulation research program
3. Recognize the contribution of the Valquiria Crew participants
4. Credit the Colombian Aerospace Force (FAC) and DIMAE when appropriate

RESEARCH COLLABORATION ACKNOWLEDGMENTS:
This research was made possible through collaboration with:
- Valquiria Crew participants who volunteered for space analog simulation
- Women AeroSTEAM for educational partnership and STEAM advancement
- Centro de Telemedicina de Colombia for technical and medical expertise
- Colombian Aerospace Force (FAC) and DIMAE for mission support

DATA PRIVACY AND ETHICAL CONSIDERATIONS:
Users of this software agree to:
- Respect the privacy and confidentiality of research participants
- Follow ethical guidelines for human subjects research
- Obtain proper institutional approvals before using with human data
- Comply with applicable data protection regulations (GDPR, HIPAA, etc.)

SCIENTIFIC INTEGRITY:
Users are expected to:
- Use the software responsibly for legitimate scientific purposes
- Report any bugs, issues, or limitations discovered during use
- Contribute improvements back to the research community when possible
- Maintain scientific standards and integrity in all applications

MODIFICATION AND DISTRIBUTION:
While this software is open-source under MIT license:
- Modifications should maintain scientific accuracy and validation
- Derivative works should preserve these additional terms and acknowledgments
- Commercial applications require separate validation and regulatory approval
- Educational use is encouraged with proper attribution

CONTACT AND SUPPORT:
For questions about appropriate use, licensing, or research collaboration:
Primary Contact: Dr. Diego Malpica MD (dlmalpicah@unal.edu.co)
Organization: Colombian Aerospace Force (FAC) - DIMAE

VERSION AND UPDATES:
This license applies to Valquiria Space Analog Physiological Data Analysis Suite
Version 2.0.1 and all subsequent versions unless explicitly modified.

By using this software, you acknowledge that you have read, understood, and 
agree to comply with both the MIT License terms and these additional conditions 
specific to the Valquiria Space Analog research project.

================================================================================
DEDICATION
================================================================================

This software is dedicated to advancing our understanding of human physiological 
adaptation in extreme environments and supporting the future of human space 
exploration. Special recognition goes to the brave Valquiria Crew members whose 
participation in space analog simulations made this research possible.

"Per aspera ad astra" - Through hardships to the stars

